    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-01T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-01T16:00:00-05:00" n="175"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d175">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/8141b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-01T16:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 1, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>106. The British Foreign Office has informed the Department that directions have
                    been given that the British Broadcasting Corporation and, so far as possible the
                    British press, should avoid all mention of <pb facs="0229" n="217"
                        xml:id="pg_217"/> General Weygand and particularly any speculation regarding
                    the possibility that he might resume the struggle.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
